    {"id":"jmiballb2025-83","text":"Depreciation means","options":["Closure of a plant due to lock out","Closure of a plant due to labour trouble","Loss of equipment over time due to wear and tear","Destruction of a plant in a fire accident"],"correct":2,"topic":"Economy","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"Depreciation is the loss of value of equipment over time due to wear and tear."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-84","text":"India changed over to the decimal system of coinage in","options":["April 1995","April 1957","April 1958","April 1959"],"correct":1,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"India adopted the decimal coinage system in April 1957."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-85","text":"The Karewa deposits of Kashmir, crucial for saffron cultivation, are","options":["Glacial moraines","Lacustrine (lake) deposits","Volcanic ash layers","Aeolian (wind-blown) sands"],"correct":1,"topic":"Geography","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"Karewas are lacustrine (old lake-bed) deposits, ideal for saffron."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-86","text":"Which soil has self-ploughing properties due to deep cracks in dry seasons?","options":["Laterite","Alluvial soil","Black soil","Red soil"],"correct":2,"topic":"Geography","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Black (regur) soil develops deep cracks on drying, giving a self-ploughing effect."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-87","text":"The book \"India Wins Freedom\" has been authored by whom?","options":["Maulana Abul Kalam Azad","Hamid Ansari","Dr. Zakir Hussain","Pandit Jawahar Lal Nehru"],"correct":0,"topic":"Books & Authors","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"'India Wins Freedom' is the autobiography of Maulana Abul Kalam Azad."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-88","text":"The Battle of Haldighati was fought in","options":["1526","1576","1748","1764"],"correct":1,"topic":"History","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The Battle of Haldighati (Maharana Pratap vs Akbar's forces) was fought in 1576."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-89","text":"'Injeel' are sacred books of","options":["Buddhists","Parsi","Christian","None of the above"],"correct":2,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Injeel refers to the Gospel, the scripture of Christians."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-90","text":"The Great Sahara Desert is located in","options":["North America","South America","Australia","Africa"],"correct":3,"topic":"Geography","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"The Sahara is in North Africa."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-91","text":"The SI unit of electric current is","options":["Volt","Ohm","Ampere","Watt"],"correct":2,"topic":"Science","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"The SI unit of electric current is the ampere."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-92","text":"Which gas is most abundant in the Earth's atmosphere?","options":["Oxygen","Carbon dioxide","Nitrogen","Argon"],"correct":2,"topic":"Science","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"Nitrogen makes up about 78% of the atmosphere."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-93","text":"mRNA vaccines differ from traditional vaccines by","options":["Using weakened viruses","Delivering genetic instructions for spike proteins","Being orally administered","None of the above"],"correct":1,"topic":"Science","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"mRNA vaccines deliver genetic instructions for cells to make the spike protein. [FLAGGED] The paper's parenthetical example ('like Covishield') is incorrect, as Covishield is a viral-vector vaccine -- the concept answer is still B."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-94","text":"Mahatma Gandhi launched his first Satyagraha in India from which of the following places?","options":["Kheda","Bardoli","Champaran","Sabarmati"],"correct":2,"topic":"History","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Gandhi's first Satyagraha in India was the Champaran Satyagraha (1917)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-95","text":"Bagdogra International Airport is located in which state?","options":["Maharashtra","West Bengal","Lakshadweep","Odisha"],"correct":1,"topic":"Geography","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Bagdogra Airport is near Siliguri in West Bengal."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-96","text":"The purpose of the Kyoto Protocol is","options":["to promote tourism","to contribute to sustainable development","to promote renewable sources of energy","to put a limit on greenhouse gas emissions by states"],"correct":3,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The Kyoto Protocol set binding limits on greenhouse-gas emissions by developed states."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-97","text":"Devaluation of a currency means","options":["reduction in the value of a currency vis-a-vis major internationally traded currencies","permitting the currency to seek its worth in the international market","fixing the value of the currency in conjunction with the movement in the value of a basket of pre-determined currencies","fixing the value of currency in multilateral consultation with the IMF, the World Bank and major trading partners"],"correct":0,"topic":"Economy","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Devaluation is a deliberate reduction in a currency's value against major foreign currencies."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-98","text":"Capital market means","options":["Mutual Funds","Money Market","Securities Market","Banking Business"],"correct":2,"topic":"Economy","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The capital market is the market for long-term securities (the securities market)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-99","text":"If the tax rate increases with the higher level of income, it shall be called","options":["Progressive Tax","Proportional Tax","Lump sum Tax","Regressive Tax"],"correct":0,"topic":"Economy","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"A tax whose rate rises with income is a progressive tax."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-100","text":"ISO 9000 is a","options":["Quality Standard Mark","Space Project","Trade Technique","Loan Security"],"correct":0,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"ISO 9000 is a family of quality-management standards."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-101","text":"The \"Chipko Movement\" originated as a protest against","options":["Nuclear power plants","Deforestation in the Himalayas","Dam construction on the Ganges","Mining in Aravallis"],"correct":1,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"The Chipko Movement was a protest against deforestation in the Himalayas."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-102","text":"A computer cannot 'boot' if it does not have the","options":["Compiler","Loader","Operating System","Assembler"],"correct":2,"topic":"Computers","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"A computer needs an operating system to boot."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-103","text":"Earth is also known as the","options":["Blue planet","Red Planet","Brown Planet","Green Planet"],"correct":0,"topic":"Science","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"Earth is called the Blue Planet because of its water cover."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-104","text":"The currency of Laos is","options":["Kip","Baht","Lira","Peseta"],"correct":0,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The currency of Laos is the kip."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-105","text":"Parliament of India consists of","options":["Council of States","President, House of the People and Council of States","House of the People and Council of States","House of the People"],"correct":1,"topic":"Polity","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Under Article 79, Parliament consists of the President, the Lok Sabha and the Rajya Sabha."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-106","text":"The person responsible for the economic model for Indian Planning","options":["Jawaharlal Nehru","P.C. Mahalanobis","Tarlok Singh","V.T. Krishnamachari"],"correct":1,"topic":"Economy","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"P. C. Mahalanobis devised the model underlying the Second Five-Year Plan."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-107","text":"Vande Mataram is composed by","options":["Rabindranath Tagore","Sharatchandra Chatterji","Bankimchandra Chatterjee","Surendranath Banerji"],"correct":2,"topic":"General Studies","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"'Vande Mataram' was composed by Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-108","text":"The \"Doctrine of Lapse\" was introduced by","options":["Lord Dalhousie","Lord Curzon","Lord Mountbatten","Lord Wellesley"],"correct":0,"topic":"History","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The Doctrine of Lapse was applied by Lord Dalhousie."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-109","text":"Article 1 of the Indian Constitution defines India as","options":["Federal State","Unitary State","Union of States","Quasi-Federal State"],"correct":2,"topic":"Polity","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Article 1 describes India, that is Bharat, as a 'Union of States'."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-110","text":"The Great Barrier Reef refers to","options":["Coral formation","Tidal waves","Hill range","Man-made walls"],"correct":0,"topic":"Geography","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"The Great Barrier Reef is the world's largest coral reef formation."},

    // ---- Legal Aptitude (111-150) ----
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-111","text":"\"The State shall make provisions for securing just and humane conditions of work and for maternity relief\" is found","options":["As a Fundamental Duty of the State","As a Directive Principle of the State Policy","As a part of the Preamble to the Constitution of India","As a Fundamental Right under Art 21 of the Constitution of India"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"This is Article 42, a Directive Principle of State Policy."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-112","text":"A writ of mandamus will not lie against","options":["President of India","Parliament","Local authorities","Courts and Tribunals"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Mandamus does not lie against the President of India (Article 361 grants immunity)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-113","text":"Where is the unwritten constitution in force?","options":["Japan","Sri Lanka","England","None of the above"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"England (the UK) is the classic example of an unwritten constitution."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-114","text":"Name the first woman advocate in India","options":["Cornelia Sorabji","Mrs. Anna Chandy","Mrs. Monica David","None of the above"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Cornelia Sorabji was India's first woman advocate."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-115","text":"Which Article of the Constitution empowers the Supreme Court to review its own judgments?","options":["Article 137","Article 143","Article 32","Article 131"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Article 137 gives the Supreme Court power to review its own judgments."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-116","text":"For how many years does a person have to be a High Court judge to become a Supreme Court Judge?","options":["3","5","6","10"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"A High Court judge of at least 5 years' standing is eligible for the Supreme Court (Article 124)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-117","text":"The 'Doctrine of Eclipse' applies to","options":["Fundamental Rights violated before 1950","Money Bills passed without Rajya Sabha's consent","Laws inconsistent with Fundamental Rights","Ordinances issued during parliamentary recess"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"Under the Doctrine of Eclipse, a pre-Constitution law inconsistent with Fundamental Rights is not dead but overshadowed, and revives if the inconsistency is removed."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-118","text":"Dower (Mahr) is a well-known branch of which law?","options":["Mohammedan Law","Hindu Law","English Law","Parsi Law"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Dower (Mahr) is a concept of Mohammedan (Muslim) law."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-119","text":"A jurist can become","options":["Supreme Court judge","High Court judge","Auditor General of India","None of the above"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"Under Article 124, a distinguished jurist may be appointed a Supreme Court judge."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-120","text":"The 'Kesavananda Bharati case' (1973) is primarily associated with","options":["Right to Property","Basic Structure Doctrine","Judicial Review","Federalism"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Kesavananda Bharati (1973) established the Basic Structure Doctrine."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-121","text":"Which of the following is NOT a constitutional body?","options":["Finance Commission","National Commission for SCs","Election Commission","NITI Aayog"],"correct":3,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"NITI Aayog is an executive (non-constitutional) body; the others are constitutional."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-122","text":"Which constitutional amendment introduced the Anti-Defection Law?","options":["42nd Amendment","44th Amendment","52nd Amendment","73rd Amendment"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The 52nd Amendment (1985) introduced the Anti-Defection Law (Tenth Schedule)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-123","text":"The minimum gap permissible between two sessions of Parliament is","options":["3 months","4 months","6 months","9 months"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"No more than six months may elapse between two sessions of Parliament (Article 85)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-124","text":"The concept of Public Interest Litigation, which has become quite popular in India, originated in","options":["England","USA","Australia","Canada"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Public Interest Litigation originated in the USA."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-125","text":"Duties and powers of the Comptroller and Auditor General are mentioned in which article?","options":["Article 137","Article 149","Article 98","Article 150"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Article 149 lays down the duties and powers of the CAG."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-126","text":"The act of unlawfully entering into another's property is called","options":["Triplication","Trover","Breach of property","Trespass"],"correct":3,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"Unlawful entry onto another's property is trespass."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-127","text":"Mixed Economy means","options":["Co-existence of small and large industries","Promoting both Agriculture and Industries in the economy","Co-existence of public and private sectors","Co-existence of rich and poor"],"correct":2,"topic":"Economy","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"A mixed economy is one in which the public and private sectors co-exist."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-128","text":"National Law Day in India is observed on","options":["10 December","26 October","15 November","26 November"],"correct":3,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"National Law Day (Constitution Day) is observed on 26 November."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-129","text":"What do you understand by the legal term \"habeas corpus\"?","options":["That the (detained) person be produced before the court","Basement rights to move freely","The same cause of damage","A claim on legal grounds"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Habeas corpus ('you shall have the body') is a writ to produce a detained person before the court. [FLAGGED] The options were partly garbled on the scan -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-130","text":"What is meant by the legal maxim \"jus cogens\"?","options":["Law of community","International law","Compelling law","Law coherent with municipal law"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"Jus cogens is a peremptory or compelling norm of law. [FLAGGED] The visible tick looked like 'International law'; the literal meaning is 'compelling law' -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-131","text":"What is meant by the legal maxim \"non compos mentis\"?","options":["A body recovered from a crime scene which is not fully decomposed","Not in possession of one's mind","Body not in a decomposed state of condition","None of the above"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Non compos mentis means not of sound mind."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-132","text":"Principle: An offer can be accepted only when the acceptor has knowledge of such offer. Facts: Mr. Arpit offers to pay a reward of Rs.10,000 to anyone who finds his watch. Mr. Mithilesh, without knowledge of the offer, finds and returns the watch. Which derivation is CORRECT?","options":["Mr. Mithilesh can claim the reward because he found and returned the watch","Mr. Mithilesh cannot claim the reward because the offer was frivolous","Mr. Mithilesh cannot claim the reward because he had no knowledge of the offer","None of the above"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude (Reasoning)","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"As acceptance requires knowledge of the offer (Lalman Shukla v Gauri Dutt), Mithilesh cannot claim the reward."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-133","text":"Principle: A registered trade union enjoys certain immunities, but not for the personal acts of its office-bearers. Facts: Soloman, Secretary of a registered Trade Union, took a bank loan for a personal purpose and did not repay it; the Bank warns of legal action. Which derivation is CORRECT?","options":["The Bank can file a suit for recovery against Soloman as he took the loan for a personal purpose and no immunity applies","The Bank can recover the loan from the Trade Union as Soloman is its Secretary","The Bank cannot initiate any action against Soloman as he is Secretary of a registered Trade Union","As Soloman did not use the loan amount for his own use, no action can be initiated against him"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude (Reasoning)","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The loan was personal, so no union immunity applies and the Bank can sue Soloman."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-134","text":"Principle: The Constitution guarantees fundamental rights, including the freedom to form associations (which implies the right to join or not to join one); but these rights are enforceable against the State, not private individuals. Facts: AB Chemicals (a private company) issued a circular restricting union activity; Navin, an employee and General Secretary of XATU, approaches the High Court alleging breach of fundamental rights. Identify the most reasonable legal proposition.","options":["The company's circular is illegal and has to be quashed by the Court","The rule restricting fundamental rights applies only to the State and not to individuals, hence Navin will not get relief from the High Court","A circular issued by a company amounts to law in the constitutional sense, hence the High Court can issue a writ as pleaded by Navin","The circular interferes with the freedom guaranteed by the Constitution, hence the High Court can issue an appropriate writ"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude (Reasoning)","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"Fundamental rights are enforceable against the State, not a private employer, so Navin gets no writ relief."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-135","text":"Principle: An agreement to do an impossible act is void. Facts: Ms. Rajani agrees with Mr. Bala to discover treasure by magic. Which derivation is CORRECT?","options":["The act is not void because the act is capable of being performed","The act is not void because it is not forbidden by law","The act is void because the agreement to discover treasure by magic is impossible","None of the above"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude (Reasoning)","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Discovering treasure by magic is impossible, so the agreement is void."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-136","text":"When both the parties to a contract are under a mistake of fact essential to the contract, the contract is","options":["Void","Voidable","Valid","None of these"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"A bilateral mistake of an essential fact makes the agreement void (s.20, Indian Contract Act)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-137","text":"Which of the following is NOT a Fundamental Right?","options":["Right to Property","Right to Equality","Right to Religion","Right against Exploitation"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The Right to Property was removed as a Fundamental Right by the 44th Amendment; it is now a legal right under Article 300A. [FLAGGED] The visible tick looked like 'Right against Exploitation' -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-138","text":"The Malimath Committee is associated with reforms in the field of","options":["Education","Domestic relations","Labour welfare","Criminal law"],"correct":3,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"The Malimath Committee dealt with reforms of the criminal justice system. [FLAGGED] The committee's name was partly illegible on the scan -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-139","text":"A person who helps another person in the commission of an offence is known as","options":["Abettor","Instigator","Accomplice","Friend"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"One who aids or abets the commission of an offence is an abettor. [FLAGGED] 'Accomplice' is also defensible -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-140","text":"A friend of the court is called","options":["Animus","Amicus curiae","In terrorem","Juris et de jure"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"easy","explanation":"Amicus curiae means 'friend of the court'."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-141","text":"Who chaired the First Law Commission that prepared the first draft of the Indian Penal Code?","options":["Warren Hastings","William Bentinck","Thomas Macaulay","Charles Hardinge"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Thomas Babington Macaulay chaired the First Law Commission and drafted the IPC."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-142","text":"What is the main objective of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC)?","options":["Decrease of oxygen","Stabilization of greenhouse gases","Increase of greenhouse gases","Increase of temperature"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude / GK","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The UNFCCC aims at stabilizing greenhouse-gas concentrations in the atmosphere. [FLAGGED] The visible tick looked like 'Increase of greenhouse gases' -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-143","text":"\"Lis pendens\" means:","options":["Awaited information","On the basis of evidence","Decision awaited","A pending suit"],"correct":3,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Lis pendens = a pending suit or litigation."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-144","text":"POTA stands for","options":["Prohibition of Terrorists Act","Prohibition of Toxic Aid","Prevention of Terrorism Act","Prevention of Terrorism and Atrocities"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"POTA is the Prevention of Terrorism Act, 2002. [FLAGGED] The visible tick looked like 'Prevention of Terrorism and Atrocities' -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-145","text":"Which of these systems is followed in India?","options":["Adversarial System","Judicial System","Inquisitorial System","None of these"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"India follows the adversarial system of justice. [FLAGGED] The visible tick looked like 'Judicial System' -- verify against the official key."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-146","text":"Which of the following is the oldest High Court in India?","options":["High Court of Madras","High Court of Calcutta","High Court of Delhi","High Court of Allahabad"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The Calcutta High Court (established 1862) is the oldest High Court in India."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-147","text":"Private International Law is also called","options":["Civil Law","Local laws","Conflict of laws","Common law"],"correct":2,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"Private International Law is also known as the conflict of laws."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-148","text":"Tort is a violation of","options":["a right in personam","a right in rem","both a right in personam and a right in rem","neither a right in personam nor a right in rem"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"hard","explanation":"A tort is the violation of a right in rem (a right available against the world at large)."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-149","text":"What is a 'caveat'?","options":["A warning","An injunction","Writ","Certiorari"],"correct":0,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"A caveat is a caution or warning entered in court."},
    {"id":"jmiballb2025-150","text":"The International Criminal Court is established by the","options":["London Declaration","Rome Statute","Paris Conference","New York Convention"],"correct":1,"topic":"Legal Aptitude","difficulty":"medium","explanation":"The International Criminal Court was established by the Rome Statute (1998)."}
